#: ../../../cmds/for.rst:2
msgid "for - perform a set of commands multiple times"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/for.rst:5
msgid "Synopsis"
msgstr "概要"

#: ../../../cmds/for.rst:7
msgid "for VARNAME in [VALUES ...]; COMMANDS ...; end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/for.rst:12
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/for.rst:14
msgid ""
"**for** is a loop construct. It will perform the commands specified by "
"*COMMANDS* multiple times. On each iteration, the local variable specified "
"by *VARNAME* is assigned a new value from *VALUES*. If *VALUES* is empty, "
"*COMMANDS* will not be executed at all. The *VARNAME* is visible when the "
"loop terminates and will contain the last value assigned to it. If *VARNAME* "
"does not already exist it will be set in the local scope. For our purposes "
"if the **for** block is inside a function there must be a local variable "
"with the same name. If the **for** block is not nested inside a function "
"then global and universal variables of the same name will be used if they "
"exist."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/for.rst:16
msgid ""
"Much like :doc:`set <set>`, **for** does not modify $status, but the "
"evaluation of its subordinate commands can."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/for.rst:18
msgid "The **-h** or **--help** option displays help about using this command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/for.rst:21
msgid "Example"
msgstr "範例"

#: ../../../cmds/for.rst:25
msgid ""
"for i in foo bar baz; echo $i; end\n"
"\n"
"# would output:\n"
"foo\n"
"bar\n"
"baz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/for.rst:34
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/for.rst:36
msgid ""
"The ``VARNAME`` was local to the for block in releases prior to 3.0.0. This "
"means that if you did something like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/for.rst:40
msgid ""
"for var in a b c\n"
"    if break_from_loop\n"
"        break\n"
"    end\n"
"end\n"
"echo $var"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/for.rst:48
msgid ""
"The last value assigned to ``var`` when the loop terminated would not be "
"available outside the loop. What ``echo $var`` would write depended on what "
"it was set to before the loop was run. Likely nothing."
msgstr ""
